What is technical Art?

Technical Art bridges the gap between artistic vision and technical implementation in game development and interactive media.

Key Responsibilities:

  • Pipeline Development: Creating tools and workflows for artists
  • Optimization: Ensuring artistic assets perform efficiently
  • Problem Solving: Resolving technical constraints while maintaining visual quality
  • Communication: Translating between art and programming teams

Technical Artist Skill set

Artistic Skills:

  • Visual design principles
  • Color theory and composition
  • Understanding of art pipelines
  • Procedural asset development
  • Animation principles

Technical Skills:

  • Scripting and programming
  • Shader development
  • Performance optimization
  • Tool development

Rendering pipelines

How Are video Game Graphics rendered?

A rendering pipeline is a sequence of operations that take the contents of a scene and display them on-screen. The pipeline transforms 3D models into 2D images through a series of calculations.

Modern rendering pipeline stages

1.Input Assembly | 2. Vertex processing | 3. Rasterization | 4. Fragment / Pixel processing | 5. Post Processing

Let’s start at the beginning

Every frame, the CPU prepares necessary data for rendering a scene, this includes:

  • Vertex buffers: The CPU organizes the 3D geometry (positions, normals, colors, texture coordinates, Material IDs) into vertex buffer which are later processed by the GPU.

  • Index buffers: If indexed drawing is used, the CPU prepares an index buffer that specifies how to assemble vertices into primitives (e.g how to form triangles and vertex positions)

  • Shader Programs: The CPU loads and compiles vertex, fragment, and possibly geometry shaders into the GPU’s memory. These shaders define how the vertex data is transformed and how pixels are shaded.

  • Uniform Buffers/Textures: The CPU also sends any global data that shaders might need, such as transformation matrices (e.g., model, view, projection matrices), lighting information, and texture data.

  • State Objects: The CPU also configures the GPU state, like which shader program to use, which textures to bind, and how to handle blending, depth testing, and rasterization.

Draw call’s

The CPU gather’s all that data, and sends it through a series of API call’s ( changes depending on the Graphics API used … DirectX, Open GL, Vulkan etc.) to the GPU. The CPU is always processing one frame ahead of the GPU.

Draw call’s

Pngall.com. (2016). Gordon Ramsay PNG | PNG All. [online] Available at: https://www.pngall.com/gordon-ramsay-png/download/157812/ [Accessed 14 Sep. 2025]. ‌

  • We can think of the CPU as the head chef giving orders (Draw Calls) to the kitchen staff = GPU.

  • The kitchen crew (GPU) are fast cooks, capable of handling complex recipes. the GPU has many small core = Many hands in the kitchen.

  • But the head chef (CPU) has a very limited amount of cores = Only a few hands.

  • If the CPU has too many unique ‘orders’ , this can overwhelm the CPU, and as a result, the GPU waits and the frame takes longer to be rendered.

What creates Draw Call’s in a scene?

Evseyenkov, D. (2023). Optimize Unity’s graphic design for mobile devices. [online] rugraphics. Available at: https://rugraphics.ru/blogs/optimizacziya-graficheskogo-dizajna-v-unity-dlya-mobilnyh-ustrojstv [Accessed 14 Sep. 2025]. ‌

Generally, each unique “thing” the GPU needs to draw requires a draw call.

  • Unique meshes: Every distinct static mesh object placed in the level.

  • Materials: Each material applied to a mesh generates a seperate draw call.

  • Dynamic objects: Objects that move or change often require new draw calls.

  • Lights: Dynamic lights casting shadows can add significant draw calls for shadow map rendering.

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Input Assembly

  • After receiving Draw call’s from the CPU the GPU enter’s the input Assembly (IA) stage. This is an essential part of the graphics pipeline. It is responsible for gathering all the data sent by the draw call:

vertex data containing the raw positions of vertices, their attributes (colors, normals, etc) and any other information and organizing this data into primitives based on the specified primitive type (e.g. Triangle, line, or point)

Vertex buffer:

v0 = (0,0,0)
v1 = (1,0,0)
v2 = (0,1,0)
v3 = (1,1,0)


Index buffer (optional) - Tells the GPU which vertices to connect together:

[0,1,2] → triangle 1
[1,3,2] → triangle 2

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Vertex processing

After the Input Assembly groups raw vertices into primitives, the GPU sends each vertex to the Vertex Processing Stage

  • this is where each individual vertex gets processed (in parallel on the GPU).
  • Each vertex starts in object (relative/local/modal) space
  • The vertex shader then multiplies it by matrices to move it through spaces:
worldPosition=Model×vertexPosition | viewPosition=View×worldPosition | clipPosition=Projection×viewPosition |

clipPosition=Projection×View×Model×vertexPosition

This is known as the MVP matrix chain which is a series of matrice calculations to get each vertex moved on to the screen space accounting for where the model is in space, where the camera is and the perpective angle from the camera.

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Rasterization

After vertex processing transforms all vertices into screen space, the Rasterization stage determines which pixels on the screen are covered by each primitive (triangle, line, or point).

Primitive Assembly: Vertices are grouped back into their original primitives
Clipping: Primitives outside the view frustum are removed or clipped
Triangle Setup: Calculate edge equations and interpolation parameters

Scan Conversion: Determine which pixels are inside each triangle
Attribute Interpolation: Smoothly blend vertex attributes (colors, UVs, normals) across the surface

Rasterization process

  • Edge Function Testing: Mathematical tests determine if a pixel center lies inside the triangle

  • Barycentric Coordinates: Calculate weights for interpolating vertex attributes

  • Fragment Generation: Each covered pixel becomes a “fragment” - a potential pixel with interpolated data

  • Early Z-Testing: Some GPUs perform depth testing here to discard occluded fragments early

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Fragment / pixel processing

The Fragment Shader (also called Pixel Shader) processes each fragment generated by rasterization. This is where the final color and appearance of each pixel is determined.

  • Fragments contain interpolated vertex data (position, color, UV coordinates, normals)
  • Fragment shaders run in parallel across hundreds or thousands of GPU cores
  • This stage handles lighting calculations, texture sampling, and material properties
  • Output is typically an RGBA color value and depth

Texture Sampling: Reading color/data from texture maps using UV coordinates
Lighting Calculations: Applying lighting models (Phong, Blinn-Phong, PBR)

Normal Mapping: Using normal maps to add surface detail
Material Properties: Applying roughness, metallic, specular properties

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Post processing

Post Processing occurs after the main scene has been rendered to a framebuffer. These effects are applied as full-screen passes, treating the rendered image as a texture.

Common Post Processing Effects:

  • Tone Mapping & Gamma Correction
  • Bloom & HDR
  • Anti-Aliasing (FXAA, TAA)
  • Depth of Field
  • Motion Blur
  • Color Grading

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Forward rendering.

Forward Rendering processes lighting calculations during the fragment shader stage for each object. Each fragment calculates lighting for all lights affecting it.

Advantages:

  • Simple and straightforward implementation
  • Good for scenes with few lights
  • Supports transparency naturally
  • Lower memory bandwidth requirements

Disadvantages:

  • Performance scales poorly with light count
  • Overdraw causes repeated lighting calculations
  • Limited number of dynamic lights

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Deferred rendering.

Deferred Rendering separates geometry rendering from lighting calculations:

G-Buffer Pass: Render all geometry to multiple render targets (position, normal, albedo, material properties)
Lighting Pass: Full-screen pass that reads from G-Buffer and calculates lighting
Forward Pass: Transparent objects rendered with forward rendering on top

Advantages:

  • Lighting cost independent of scene complexity
  • Supports many dynamic lights efficiently
  • Decouples shading from geometry complexity

Disadvantages:

  • Higher memory bandwidth (G-Buffer)
  • No transparency support in deferred pass
  • MSAA is expensive
  • Overdraw in lighting pass for small lights

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Modern Hybrid Approaches

Tiled/Clustered Rendering: Modern engines often use hybrid approaches:

  • Tiled Forward: Divide screen into tiles, cull lights per tile
  • Clustered Deferred: 3D clustering for better light culling
  • Forward+: Forward rendering with tiled light culling

These approaches combine the benefits of both forward and deferred rendering while minimizing their respective drawbacks.

Performance Considerations:

Light Count: Deferred better for >10-20 lights
Transparency: Forward required for transparent objects
Memory: Deferred uses more VRAM for G-Buffer
Platform: Mobile often prefers forward due to bandwidth limitations

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

Overdraw

Unreal Art Optimization. (2019). Oskar Świerad. [online] Available at: https://unrealartoptimization.github.io/book/profiling/view-modes/ [Accessed 14 Sep. 2025]. ‌

Overdraw refers to rendering the same Pixel location
multiple times in one frame.

  • The GPU renders the same pixel multiple times, wasting
    resources.

  • Every time a pixel is drawn, the GPU has to run the
    material’s pixel shader. This calculates the final colour,
    considering textures, lighting, etc. complex shaders are
    expensive!

  • GPUs have a limit to how many pixels they can fill (Draw)
    per second (Fill rate), high overdraw consumes this budget
    rapidly.

Android Developers. (2024). Materials and Shaders. [online] Available at: https://developer.android.com/games/optimize/materials [Accessed 14 Sep. 2025]. ‌

The main culprit of Overdraw is Transparency /
Translucency.

  • Transparent objects must be drawn after opaque objects
    are finished (so we can see the opaque stuff through
    them). They often need to blend with what’s already
    drawn in the pixel behind them.

  • Heavy overlap such as layers of glass, dense particle
    effects (smoke, sparks etc) each particle card overlaps
    others, volumetric fog covering large areas also causes
    severe Overdraw issues.

Anti-Aliasing

Anti-aliasing is a graphics technique used to eliminate jagged edges / pixelation or aliasing artifacts that occur when game engines render smooth 3D shapes on pixel-based displays. It smooths the appearance of edges to create a more realistic image.

  • FXAA (Fast Approximate Anti-Aliasing)

  • MSAA (Multisample Anti-Aliasing)

  • TAA (Temporal Anti-Aliasing)

  • SSAA (Supersample Anti-Aliasing)

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

FXAA (Fast Approximate Anti-Aliasing)

FXAA occurs in the final stage of the rendering pipeline, the Post-Processing stage, and it attempts to seeks outs edges within a rendered scene by analysing the luminance and color values of neighbouring pixels in an image to identify areas where aliasing is likely to occur and apply a controlled blur to those areas to reduce the aliasing effect.

Advantages:

  • Very good performance with minimal GPU cost compared to MSAA or SSAA.
  • Great for real-time applications
  • Works on the final image, so it doesn’t require changes to shaders or geometry.
  • Works on textures, UI, and transparent objects, unlike MSAA which mainly affects geometry edges.

Disadvantages:

  • FXAA smooths edges by blurring them, which can reduce fine texture detail.
  • Text and UI can appear softer or slightly blurred.
  • Not as precise as other techniques.
  • Works on the rendered image, so it can’t prevent aliasing that occurs inside shaders or during sampling.

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

MSAA (Multisample Anti-Aliasing)

Junzzzz (2022). 课程 5-7 总结 - 学习笔记. [online] Github.io. Available at: https://junzzzz.github.io/study-docs/games-course/games101/summary-5-7/ [Accessed 14 Sep. 2025]. ‌
- **MSAA** occurs during the **rasterization** stage of the rendering pipeline and works by taking multiple samples per pixels overlapping geometry edges (2x, 4x etc.) and determines how many of these samples are covered by the geometry - After sampling, the colors from the various sample points are averaged to produce the final color for the pixel. This averaging helps to smooth out the jagged edges that would otherwise be visible if only a single sample point were used.

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

MSAA (Multisample Anti-Aliasing)

Advantages

  • Provides much sharper, cleaner edges than FXAA
  • Doesn’t blur textures or UI since it only targets geometry edges.
  • Only geometry edges are sampled multiple times, not the entire shading pipeline.
  • Offer’s good image quality at a fraction of SSAA’s performance cost

Disadvantages

  • Still more expensive than FXAA or TAA.
  • Performance hit scales with sample level (2x, 4x, 8x)
  • Only smooths geometry edges.
  • Doesn’t fix aliasing inside shaders, alpha-tested geometry (like foliage), or sub-pixel detail.
  • Increases VRAM usage because it requires storing multiple samples in the render targets.
  • Does not work well with deferred rendering (used in unreal by default).

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

TAA (Temporal Anti-Aliasing)

TAA, just like FXAA, occurs in the Post-Processing stage of the rendering pipeline and works by utilizing data (History Buffers) from previous frames to create a more refined image quality. TAA samples pixels across multiple frames and blends them together to reduce aliasing artifacts.

TAA is the most popular form of Anti-Aliasing in video game rendering and is the default AA used in Unreal engine.

Advantages

  • Excellent and reducing temporal aliasing when moving the camera.
  • Works well with Deferred rendering unlike MSAA
  • Works on everything in the final image, including alpha-tested geometry (foliage, particles, etc.)
  • Provides smoothness close to super-sampling at a fraction of the cost.

Disadvantages

  • Can make the image slightly soft or blurry compared to MSAA/SSAA.
  • Fine texture details can look smudged.
  • Can generate ghost trails on fast moving object or transparent effects.
  • Needs stable motion history, otherwise, errors build up.

FGCT5016 : Technical Art | Liam Lacey | 25/26

SSAA (Supersample Anti Aliasing)

SSAA occurs at the rasterization stage, and works by rendering the scene at a higher resolution than the target resolution for your display. A 1920x1080 target resolution with a SSAA 2x might render the scene at 3840x2140. It then downsample’s the image back to the targeted display resolution averaging pixel colours based on the higher resolution sample.

Advantages

  • Highest image quality out of all AA.
  • No blur (unlike FXAA or TAA).
  • Reduces aliasing in geometry, textures, shaders and transparency.
  • Works with any rendering pipeline (forward, deferred).
  • Since you are rendering more pixels, you capture finer detail.

Disadvantages

  • Extremely expensive - rendering at 2x resolution = 4x pixel cost.
  • Basically multiplies GPU workload massively.
  • With PBR shading and post-processing, performance hit is often unjustifiable.
  • Mostly used in offline rendering, high-end screenshots or non real-time applications.
